&#xa0;
[normal]Written Evidence by[bold] Professor P.C. Lee[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Executive summary:[bold]As a 
[normal]past president of the Primate Society of Great Britain, a scientific body established for the
[normal] promotion of research into primate biology, conservation, and captive care, I would like to 
[normal]provide
[normal] some comments 
[normal]for
[normal] this enquiry.
[normal] My expertise is not with regard to the numbers of primates held privately, but rather with the fundamental issues of the adequacy of the protection of primate welfare 
[normal]for pet primates 
[normal]and the appropriateness of the keeping 
[normal]of primates as “pets”. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]As a result of my 
[normal]39 years of 
[normal]experience with non-human primate biology, behaviour and conservation
[normal] both in the wild and captivity
[normal], I can perceive no ethical, husbandry, conservation or historical justifications for continuing to 
[normal]allow the keeping of primates as companion animals in the UK.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]a)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Should primates be kept in private ownership as “pets”?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]b)[bold]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Are primates adequat[bold]ely protected by current legislation[bold]?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
